        "{@--1@} <ab>N.</ab> of a range of \nmountains which separates Hindustān\nproper from the Deccan or south;\nit is one of the seven {%Kulaparvatas%}\n<ab>q. v.</ab>, and forms the southern limit\nof Madhyadeśa; see <ls>Ms. 2. 21.</ls>\n[According to a legend, the Vindhya\nmountain, being jealous of the mount\nMeru (or Himālaya) demanded that\nthe sun should revolve round himself\nas about Meru, which the sun declined\nto do; whereupon the Vindhya began\nto rise higher and higher so as to \nobstruct the path of the sun and moon.\nThe gods being alarmed sought the aid\nof the sage Agastya, who approached\nthe mountain and requested that by\nbending down he would give him an\neasy passage to the south, and that he\nwould retain the same position till his\nreturn. This Vindhya consented to do\n(because according to one account, he\nregarded Agastya as his teacher); but\nAgastya never returned from the south,\nand Vindhya never attained the height\nof Meru]. ",
        "{@--2@} A hunter. "
